# Chicago Input Patch

Experimental WinMM proxy DLL to enable modern USB controllers in Windows 95 / early DirectX era games.

### Why this project exists
Many games from 1995–1999 (Doom 95, Resident Evil, Soul Reaver, etc.) rely on legacy WinMM joystick APIs (`joyGetNumDevs`, `joyGetDevCaps`, `joyGetPosEx`).  
On modern Windows, the physical gameport and `vjoyd.vxd` driver no longer exist → games crash or see 0 devices.  
This proxy intercepts those calls, fakes a classic gameport, and allows USB input redirection.

### Features
- Fake joystick (returns 1 device + plausible caps) to pass strict checks in Doom 95
- Forwarding of all non-intercepted WinMM functions to `winmm_real.dll`
- Safe fallbacks for timer functions (`timeGetTime`, etc.)
- Ready for future USB redirection (XInput/DirectInput planned)

### Requirements
- Windows (tested on 10/11)
- MinGW-w64 (g++) for compilation
- Original `winmm.dll` renamed to `winmm_real.dll`

### Installation / Testing
1. Rename `C:\Windows\System32\winmm.dll` to `winmm_real.dll` and copy to game folder.
2. Copy compiled `winmm.dll` to game folder.
3. Run the game executable.

### Building
Use the GitHub Actions workflow (`.github/workflows/build.yml`) — it compiles automatically on push.  
Or locally:

```bash
g++ -shared -o winmm.dll winmm_proxy.cpp winmm.def -lwinmm -Wl,--subsystem,windows -s -Os
